title: MCP Installation

!! Requirements

# ''Node.js'' (v24 or later)
# ''TiddlyWiki'' installed globally: `npm install -g tiddlywiki`
# ''Claude Code'' (CLI, VS Code extension, or desktop app)

!! Plugin Setup

The `wikilabs/tw-mcp` plugin is not part of TiddlyWiki core. TiddlyWiki needs to know where to find it.

!!! 1. Set `TIDDLYWIKI_PLUGIN_PATH`

This environment variable tells TiddlyWiki where to look for third-party plugins.

; Linux / macOS
: Add to `~/.bashrc` or `~/.zshrc`:

```
export TIDDLYWIKI_PLUGIN_PATH="/path/to/your/plugins"
```

; Windows
: Set via System Environment Variables or in your terminal profile:

```
set TIDDLYWIKI_PLUGIN_PATH=C:\path\to\your\plugins
```

The path must point to the directory that ''contains'' the `wikilabs/` folder (not to `wikilabs/` itself).

!!! 2. Add the plugin to your wiki

In your wiki's `tiddlywiki.info` file, add the plugin:

```json
{
  "plugins": [
    "wikilabs/tw-mcp"
  ]
}
```

!!! 3. Verify

Run from your wiki directory:

```
tiddlywiki . --mcp
```

If the plugin is not found, you will see:

> ''Warning: Cannot find plugin 'wikilabs/tw-mcp' ''
> ''Error: Unknown command: mcp''

Double-check that `TIDDLYWIKI_PLUGIN_PATH` is set correctly.

!! Claude Code Configuration

Add a `.mcp.json` file to your wiki directory:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "tiddlywiki": {
      "type": "stdio",
      "command": "tiddlywiki",
      "args": [".", "--mcp", "label=claude"]
    }
  }
}
```

Then start Claude Code from that directory. The MCP server will be available automatically.

!!! Alternative: Set the plugin path in `.mcp.json`

Instead of a global environment variable, you can set `TIDDLYWIKI_PLUGIN_PATH` per-server using the `env` field:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "tiddlywiki": {
      "type": "stdio",
      "command": "tiddlywiki",
      "args": [".", "--mcp", "label=claude"],
      "env": {
        "TIDDLYWIKI_PLUGIN_PATH": "/path/to/your/plugins"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

This sets the variable only for the MCP server process, without requiring it in your shell profile.